{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2115].
  {panel}

I want to be able to create a notification scheme based on issue priority, e.g. a scheme that will only notify members of Blocker or Critical issues, rather than all issues by default.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2106].
  {panel}

The concept is similar to email forwarding.  You are looking at an issue and you know that some other person would benefit from knowing about changes to an issue, so you "forward" the issue to them.  The person or persons you are forwarding the issue to would receive an email notification letting them know that you have forwarded the issue to them.  The forward recipient(s) would have the ability to delete the forward if they decided at some point that they were no longer interested.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2088].
  {panel}

I'm trying to use the UserBrowser screen in the Administration options to find the details of a user, and all I have to go on is his name.  I got that from a New Issue email notification, which doesn't contain his email address; I can't just view the issue in question as it was lost in the recent server crash and is no longer there (that's why I'm wanting to email him...)

Unfortunately, the screen only allows for filtering on Email address or Group, so I'm having to page through all 600+ users to find him.  It would have been useful if I could have filtered the list on (a case-insensitive substring match of) the Fullname field as well.  For that matter, I can think of circumstances when filtering on Username might be useful too, so why not add that too and have all the fields available for filtering?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2067].
  {panel}

JIRA sends out a lot of emails. This is fine. But the emails that are sendt out to the current user when the same user does changes only fills up the mailbox.

Each user can turn off this option, but it would be nice if administrator could do this for all users.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2060].
  {panel}

We need a way to give our customers ability to browse a project, but limited only to the issues they have created.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2026].
  {panel}

I think it would be useful if, when there is no filter selected, either manually, or stored in the session, and a user clicks on the 'Find Issues' link, if the page would display the same contents as clicking the 'Filter: All' link.

I know that I've clicked on 'find issues' many times, only to have my filter selection cleared, and then either have to click on 'Filter: All', or the 'Filters' quick link to select a filter.  It would be a time saver it the list filters showed up by default if there was no filter selected.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2020].
  {panel}

a generic time tracking report seems like a good option. Instead of only having the possibility to generate a time tracking report for one project at a time only, it might be handy to generate a list with the “time bars” as can be seen on top of one project’s time tracking report. This list can be custom generated, eg. One can choose to have a list of all projects, one or more project groups and /or one or more projects. The existing time tracking report may continue to exist, of course. 

A “report” button on the JIRA portal would be nice though. We consider the current place where one can generate a time tracking report quite clumsy to use.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2015].
  {panel}

While issues assigned to me is useful, the personal roadmap feature is even more critical so you can quickly identify the specific issues for the current version you are working on.  Allow configuring it as a portlet so it shows on the home page.
